[1] Human
[2] Feline

******
[1] Human
Date: Mon 27 Mar 2018
Source: Folkhalsomyndigheten (Public Health Agency of Sweden) [in Swedish, machine trans., edited]
https://www.folkhalsomyndigheten.se/smittskydd-beredskap/utbrott/aktuella-utbrott/humanfall-med-salmonellatyp-vanlig-hos-katter/


During the 1st months of 2018, many cats have developed salmonellosis. The disease has also been confirmed in small birds, which is the likely source of infection for the cats according to the Swedish Veterinary Medicine Agency (SVA).

About 10 people have now been infected with _Salmonella_ types common to small birds and cats. For some cases, there is also a confirmed connection to a cat with salmonellosis. The majority who have been infected are children in pre-school age. The cases are located in Kalmar, Stockholm, Varmland, Vastra Gotaland, Orebro, and Ostergotland counties.

Since salmonella can infect human beings from small birds and cats, hand hygiene is important. Wash your hands thoroughly after cleaning the litter boxes and after contact with the birdfeeder, and as always before handling food. Gloves protect when handling dead or sick birds. Also pay attention to the symptoms in family cats. Children, especially young children, should not come into contact with a cat who is ill.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
